{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_beetlebailey_ver01/data/sn88068010/0029455614A/1921031801/0087.xml":{"full_text":"DOTSJDASHES\nWIRE NEWS OF\nTHE WEEK\nPeace Notes.\nThe German federal council has\nadopted the government's draft law\nproviding for the definite dissolution\nof all German civilian guards and\nself defense organizations. Bavaria's\nseven votes were the only ones cast\nin opposition to the measure. This\nthreatens to bring to a head the long\nexpected clash between the central\ngovernment and Bavaria,\nThe chambers of commerce through-\nout Wurttemburg, In a Joint appeal\nto trade, commerce and industry and\nthe population in general, urge a boy-\ncott against English, French and Bel-\ngian, goods until the allies revoke\nallies against the Germans along the\nRhine.\nSecretary of War Weeks announced\nthat Major General Allen, in command\nof the American army of occupation\nin Germany, is under instructions to\nmake the orders of the Rhineland\ncommission with regard to collections\nof customs from the Germans the or\nders for bis forces.\nOberhausen, six miles east of Run\nrort and seven miles northwest of Es\nsen, has been entered by the allies,\naccording to a Central News dispatch\nfrom Paris. Entry was made' without\nincident.\nVague hints that work throughout\nthe Ruhr district of Germany will\ncease within the next few days, as the\nimmediate result of allied occupation\nof Duisburg, Dusseldorf and Ruhrort\nand the seizure of customs, were made\nby German mine operators, civil offi\ncers and workmen recently.\nIt was stated at the French foreign\noffice that negotiations were under\nway between the French embassy in\nWashington and the -state department\nin an effort to induce President\nHarding to favor acceptance of a modi\nfied League of Nations.\nSurrender of all German arms in\nthe occupied areas has been demand\ned by General Gaucher, commanding\nthe allied occupation forces. Strict\nsearch of all houses will follow fail\nure to deliver weapons to the mill\ntary, he said.\nThe penalties imposed upon Ger-\nniany will cease only when a satisfac\ntory solution of the questions of rep\narations, disarmament and war crim\ninals has been accepted by the allies.\nThe supreme council so decided at a\nrecent night session.\nWashington.\nA strong odor of crude petroleum\nemanates from the sudden drive for\nthe ratification of the 25 million dol\nlar Colombian treaty, in the opin\nion of Senator Borah and other sen\nators who have been digging into the\nscheme. They are preparing to air\ntheir discoveries when the senate re\nsumes consideration of the treaty.\nA cow has been offered President\nHarding by a Libertyville, 111., man\nwho, in a letter received at the\nWhite House, said it was his hobby\nto \"raise very good Jersey cows and\nto place them where they will be\nmost appreciated.\"\nLieut. Col. Theodore Roosevelt was\nsworn in as assistant secretary of the\nnavy within a few hours after con\nfirmation of his nomination by the\nsenate. He immediately received the\nnaval officers and civilian employees\non duty at the department.\nThe primary object of the visit of\nRene Viviani, former French premier,\nto this country late this month is to\nendeavor to prevent the writing of\na separate peace between America\nand Germany. Viviani is coming as\nthe official representative of his gov\nernment, ostensibly to extend greet\nings to President Harding, as the new\nAmerican executive.\nThe wheat surplus for export and\ncarry-over of the United States and\nCanada is 165 million bushels, accord\ning to estimates of the bureau of mar\nkets based on official and commercial\nreports, it was said recently at the\ndepartment of agriculture.\nDomestic.\nThe protection of the Kansas indus\ntrial law against reduction of wages\nand increase of working hours is to\nbe sought by tUe packing house work\nmen in Kansas, according to an an\nnouncement by the special conference\nof packing house workmen, who are\npreparing plans tor combating the\nplan of the packers to reduce wages\nand abrogate the 8-hour working day.\nli\nThe future of the department of\ncommerce in its abilities to meet the\nneeds of trade and industry must\nawait the \"thorough reorganization of\nthe whole executive machinery\" now\nbeing undertaken by the Joint congres\nsional reorganization committee. Sec\nretary Hoover said recently.\nPostmaster General Hays is looking\nfor a $50,000 a year railroad official\nto take the $5,000 Job of second assist\nant postmaster general, who has su\npervision of the railway mail service,\nChe air mall and allied activities.\nIn a telegram to Senator A. B. I\nCummins, chairman of the senate\ncommittee on interstate commerce.\nPresident B. M. Jewell of the rail-.\nroad department of the American\nFederation of Labor, and six other\nunion heads, requested \"a thorough\nInvestigation as to what is wrong\nWith ttlA milrnflrio anil vhn 4a ra.\nsponsible for the present unjustifl-\nable and unnecessary situation.\nencephalitis lethargies, the mys\nterious disease that causes Its vic\ntims to sleep for days and sometimes\nweeks before their deaths, killed\nI thirty-one Chicagoans during the first\neleven weeks of 1921, according\nthe city health records.\nto\nA general move by the nation's rail\nroads to cut war time wage scales,\n'ng forecast by rail officials, appears\nl be in full swing. Following the\nlead of several lines, which earlier\nbad announced cuts, the New York\nI Central and New York, New Haven\nI Hartford railroads in the East, and\nvirtually every railroad in the west,\nhave announced proposed wage reduc\ntions.\nA referendum strike vote of all\npacking house employees was author\nized at a conference of workers' dele\ngates' at Omaha as word came from\nWashington that President Harding\nbad referred the packing labor situ\nation to the department of labor for\nmention.\nApproximately ten thousand work-\nsrs in misses' and children's dress\nfactories have gone on strike in New\nYork. It was announced at the head\nquarters of the International Ladies'\nGarment Workers' Union, where it\nwas asserted that the industry in\nGreater New York was virtually tied\nup.\nSouthwest\nServices at a Kansas City Metho\ndist Episcopal church were conduct-\nad recently without pipe organ music.\nThieves had broken into the church\nand disappeared with the motor that\nsupplied air for the bellows. Noth\ning else, according to the minister,\nwas stolen.\nGreen bugs thread. the wheat crop\nin practically every producing county\nin Oklahoma, having swept up from\nTexas and invaded fields through Ok\nlahoma to the Kansas border, accord\ning to a statement of the Oklahoma\nstate board of agriculture.\nt f\nThe Arkansas general assembly\nadjourned sine die, its closing hours\nbeing marked by the withdrawal of\nimpeachment proceedings against\nJudge John W. Wade of Little Rock,\nwho appeared before both branches\nand apologized.\nThe country 8 flour supplies are\nrunning low because grain specula\ntors have thrown the wheat market\ninto an erratic and excitable state,\naccording to a statement issued by\nSenator Capper of Kansas. The sena\ntor declared that flour production has\nfallen off 25 per cent.\ni\nGovernor Mechem has appointed\nHolm D. Bursum of Socorro United\nStates senator from New Mexico to\nsucceed A. B. Fall, now secretary ol\nthe interior.\n\nForeign.\nDr. Walter Simons, the German\nforeign minister, and the other Ger\nman envoys to the London conference\nhave received a vote of confidence ol\nthe German cabinet and it is not con\nsidered that there is any danger of a\ngovernmental crisis.\nThe American farmer boys who\ncame to Germany with a shipload ol\ncattle recently, have left Berlin for\nBremen, from which port they will\nreturn to America on board the\nsteamer New Rochelle.\nThe provisional government of\nFiume has refused to recognize Wil\nbur Keblinger, American consul. In\nits note the provisional government\nsays: \"We, as a sovereign state,\ncannot recognize an American con\nsul until the United States formally\nrecognizes Fiume as a nation.\"\nQueen Marie of Rumania intends\nto visit America soon, and she de\nclared she believed King Ferdinand\nwould accompany her at least as far\nas New York City. She said, how\never, that he would return immedi\nately to Europe, as it was probable\nhe would not be able to spare much\ntime because cf his official duties.\nA dozen or more insurrections are in\nprogress throughout Russia and the\nanti-boishevist movement daily is en\ncouraging other, uprisings, say Warsaw\nRussians, who assert they are gaining\nconfidence of the ultimate success of\nthe counter revolutionary movement\nthey learn of fresh anti-soviet\nforces appearing from Odessa north\nward. A Belgian guard was wounded by\na bullet fired by an unidentified per\nson in the streets of Duisburg, accord\ning to a dispatch from ttat city to the\nDerniere Hour. The circumstances of\nthe shooting have not been disclosed,\nout an inquiry is under way.\nThe recent census In Switzerland\nhas caused much disappointment.\nShowing a population of 3,850,000, or\nonly 100,000 more than that of ten\nyears ago. It bad been expected\npopulation\" of 4 million would be in\ndlcated.\nCABINET TALKS\nOF TRADE TIE-UP\nConsideration of Busines Pro-\ngram by.Administration at\nthe Recent Meeting.\nTHE PRESIDENT IS OPTIMISTIC\nHarding Take Rosy View of Trade\nOutlook After Interviews With\nHeads of Big Interests.\nWashington. How to boost Ameri\ncan business at home and abroad was\nthe principal subject of discussion at\nthe meeting of President Harding with\ncablet tte other day\nThe President took an optimistic\nview of. the present period of business\ndepression, reporting to his official ad\nvisors the substance of the talks he\nhas had in the last few days with the\nheads of great industries, like James\nA. Far r ell of the United States steel\ncorporation.\nThe information that has come to\nthe President in this way is that the\nlow tide of the business depression\nhas been passed and that conditions\nare beginning to improve, particularly\nin those industries that were the first\nto be hit by the buying slump and\nfall in prices.\nWould Foster Trade Expansion,\nMr. Harding directed the cabinet dis\ncussion to the consideration of defi\nnite policies for fostering the expan\nsion of domestic and foreign com\nmerce, which he sums up as the pro\nmotion of national prosperity, one of\nthe highest functions of government\nThe President indicated that he\nfavored the lifting of restrictions im\nposed on industrial and agricultural\nindustries and a greater degree of co\noperation between the government and\nbusiness activities of the country.\nWhile he drew no invidious compari-\nsons, he left no doubt that he intend\ned to effect a change from the pro\nfessional attitude of the Wilson ad\nministration in seeking to apply all\npractical theories to the solution of\nproblems of trade and production.\nIn the field of foreign commerce, the\nPresident cited the tact that the lack\nof government co-operation and out\nright restrictions bad served to place\nAmerican business at a disadvantage\nin competing with foreigners whose\ngovernments are extremely paternal\nistic in the promotion of foreign trade.\nbuch foreign paternalism takes the\nform of government subsidies of ship\nimes ana me extension ot DanKlng and\nmarketing facilities to exporters.\nIMMIGRANTS TO THE FARMS\nNew Chief of Government Bureau\nAnnounces Plans to Relieve\nCities of the Country.\nWashington. Plans to divert immi\ngrants from the cities and industrial\ncenters and to co-ordinate agencies\nof the departments of interior, agri\nculture and labor to place the new\ncomers on small farms were an\nnounced today by W. W. Husband,\ncommissioner general of immigration.\n\"Our plan,\" lie said, \"is not to re\nplace American farmers with foreign\ners, but to create new farms and\nmake new farmers, thereby Increas\ning the resources of the nation.\nOur plan is not to scatter these\npeople out in sparsely settled sec\ntions. Neither do we plan to start\nforeign settlement communities, but\nwe plan to group them, somewhat on\nthe European village plan, and offer\nthem the advantages of expert agri\ncultural and home demonstration in\nstruction through the department ot\nagriculture, and to aid them in tak\ning udvantage ot the farm loan act.\"\nHARDING INTO WAGE FIGHT\nDispute Between the Packers and\nTheir Employes Finally Has\nReached the White House.\nWashington. The wage dispute of\nthe packers with their employees has\nbeen put up to President Harding.\nSecretary Davis, an hour before the\ncabinet meeting, called at the White\nMouse with a portfolio of papers bear\ning on the case and went into Presi\ndent Harding's office.\nThe matter was expected to be dis\ncussed at the cabinet meeting, which\nlast week decided to mako the offer\nof government mediation.\nDavis and Harding agreed that a\ncommission composed of Davis, Sec\nretary ot Commerce Hoover and Sec\nretary of Agriculture Wallace would\nsit as a mediation commission to hear\nboth sides of the dispute.\nThe packers agreed to this form of\nmediation, Davis said, and be is now\nwaiting on the employees who are con\nducting a referendum.\nWin Schools From Radicals.\nDavenport, la. In one of the most\nspirited school elections ever held in\nDavenport, the socialists, victors a\nyear ago, were overwhelmingly de\nfeated recently and their control of\nthe administration broken.\nScoffing Sent Poet to Death.\nSan Francisco. Because the verses\nof George Redman of San Francisco\naroused naught but laughter and ridi\ncule be drank poison recently and\nleaped into the Pacific Ocean, the\npolice declare.\nSERUM TREATMENT IS\nCHOLERA PREVENTIVE)\nBest Plan to Keep Everything\nClean Around Pens.\nMost Important Factor in Control of\nDisease Is to Recognize It Before\nIt Gets Started Use Good\nDisinfectant.\nCholera Is aiways dreaded at any\nseason. Swine may escape nnd every\nfanner hopes his will, hut one never\nknows. The only safe way is lo be\nenreful to keep everything clean\naround the pens- and allow no chance\ntor the Infection.\nme serum treatment la n pre\nventive, not o cure. After the disease\nstarts it is too Inte to save the herd.\nmese suggestions for the preven\ntion nnd control of the disease have\nThere Is No Profit In Unhealthy Hog\nAnimals Kept Under Clean Condi\ntions, as on Good Pastures, Are Bet\nter Able to' Resist Cholera and\nOther Diseases.\nbeen made by the agricultural expert-\nment station veterinarian, University\nof Wisconsin.\nA most important factor in the con\ntrol of the hog cholera Is to recognize\nthe disease before It has had time to\nget n deatlihoid. This can be accom-\npllshed best by advising swine raisers I\nto report promptly to the proper au\nthorities every case of sickness in\nhogs.\nThe only successful weapon of de\nfense against the enemy, hog cholera,\nIs blood from hogs that have been\nmade highly resistant to the disease.\nThis product is known as anti-hog-\ncholera serum and prevents the dis-\nease germ from becoming entrenched\nIn the hog s body. The earlier the\nserum treatment is administered the\nbetter the results are sure to be.\nWhenever hog cholera Is suspected\nor known to exist on any premises\nthe owner Is required to report the\nfact to the local board of health. It\nIs their duty Immediately to notify\nthe state veterinarian ond post a quar\nantine notice to warn the pnblic of\nthe danger.\nLiberal applicotions of any good\ncommercial liquid disinfectant to the\ntroughs and pens and a plentiful\nscattering of slacked lime on tlu lloors\nand runways are effective wnvs to\nkeep the disease from gaining access\nto a hog pen nnd to prevent it from\nspreading if it does get n foothold.\nFIX RATE OF DEPRECIATION\nOn Some Buildings It Will Run\nas\nHigh as 3 or 4 Percent Ma.\nchinery Varies Widely.\nOne per cent depreclutiou might suf\nfice os'o charge against a very sub\nstmitlnl brick or stone building. On\nseme frame buildings the rae will run\nas high as 3 or 4 per cent. Against\nfarm machinery the rate varies even\nmore widely. It may run betweeen\n5 and 20 per cent, nnd depends prln\nelpnljy upon the Implement itself and\nIn the way it is used. The office of\nfarm management, United States De\npartment of Agriculture, believes that\nn rate somewhere between 7 and 12\nper cent will be nearly correct for\nmost farm machinery. It is largely\na matter for Individual observation,\nas no two Tonus ure exactly alike in\nthis respect.\nNOAH'S ARK UP TO DATE\nFrom the time of Noah when\nthe dove brought the green back,\nhoming pigeons have been of\nconstant service to mankind.\nThat well-bred stock of this\nbreed Is desirable Is shown by\na live-stock owner In Henrrco\ncounty, Virginia. He lists 22\nhoming pigeons of pure breed\ning among other live stock en\nrolled In the Better Sires Bet\nter Stock campaign.\nCARE WITH SWEET POTATOES\nWell to Remember In Preparing Bed\nThat Diseased Seed Will\nProduce Poor Plants.\nIn \"bedding sweet potatoes, it is well\nto remember that diseased potatoes\nwill produce diseased plants, which In\nturn will produce n diseased crop. Ex\nercise cure to get clean, healthy plants\nend grow uio crop in toll that Is dis\nRIGHT TIF'E TO\nPLANT COWPEAS\nWait Until Soil, Is Thoroughly\nWarm and Danger of Cold\nWeather Has Passed.\nPUN FOR SEED PRODUCTION\nMost Practical Method is to Use Or\ndinary Grain Drill Sow Broad\ncast or In Drill Rows for For.\nage or Green Manuring.\nMM\n(Prepared by the United States Depart\nment of Agriculture.)\nCo. .ieus should not be sown until\n(he soil has become thoroughly\nwarmed and all danger of cold weath\ner Is past After that time they con\nbe sown whenever moistuje conditions\nare favorable. When sown in cold,\nwet soil, cowpea seed will either rot\nor give a poor stand of unhealthy\nplants. The latest date for profitable\nsowing, however, Is at least 90 days\nbefore the first killing frost.\nThe time of sowing will depend\nlargely upon the purpose- for which\nthe crop Is grown. If grown for seed\nor hay, the seed should be sown short\nly after the corn crop. For green\nmanuring, pasturage or hay, cowpea s\nsown as late as the first of August In\nthe South will make considerable\ngrowth. When cowpens ore to follow\nwheat or oats, they should 'be sown nt\nthe earliest possible moment after. e\ncrop Is cut.\nRate of Sowing.\nThe best method for the production\nof seed is to sow In rows about three\nfeet apart, with the seeds from two to\nthree Inches apart In the row. Al\nthough n corn planter may be used for\nsowing In this way, the most practical\nmethod is to use- the ordinary grain\ndrill, stopping part of the grain cups\nso as to leave the rows about three\nfeet apart and setting the drill the\nsame as when sowing about two bush-\nels of wheat to the acre.\nWhen cowpeas ore grown for forage\nor green manuring the seeds ore sown\nbroadcast or In drill rows six tn eight\nCowpeas, Showing Seed Pods.-\nInches apart. The grain drill set' to\nsow about one and one-half bushels of\nwheat to the acre will be fouud most\nsatisfactory. If grown for siluge with\ncorn, the corn and cowpeas can be\nsown In one operation, using the ordi\nnary corn planter, if cowpeas are\nsown in corn at the last cultivation,\nthe common practice is to sow the\nseeds broadcast at the rate of 1 to l',4\nbushels to the acre and cover theiu\nwith a cultivator.\nAnother Method.\nAnother method Is to sow with, a\none-horse wheat drill at the rate of\nabout 45 pounds to the acre, sowing\ntwo or three rows of cowpeas between\nthe rows of corn. Cowpeas nnd corn\nare sometimes sown thickly together\nfor hay with excellent results, using\nabout ontr-hulf to one bushel; of corn\nand one bushel of cowpeas to the acre.\nHowever, when corn makes a very\nheavy growth cowpeas will not give\nvery good results on account of the\nshade and lack of moisture.\nThe quantity of seed to be sown to\nthe acre varies according to the\nmethod, of sowing. With rows 24 to\n40 Inches apart, about 30 to 40 pounds\nof seed to the acre will be required.\nWhen sown broadcast', for. bay. green\nmanuring or soiling-about Uft pounds\nof seed. to the acre will be ample.\nUSING TEMPORARY PASTURES\nOne Advantage for Sheep Raising Is\nImprovement of Soil, Especially\nWith Legumes.\nOne advantage In using temporary\npastures for sheep raising Is the im\nprovement of the soil., say specialists\nof the United States Department of\nAgriculture. The greatest demand\nupon the soli is avoided by not requir\ning the crops to mature seed. All the\nmanure is distributed upon the\nground, together with all uneaten\nparts of the crop.- With legume for\nages the gain to the soil is especially\nvaluable and allows production of still\nlarger crops which- are again returned\nto the land diminished only by the\nmaterials contained In the Increased\nelse of lambs or ewes while on that\n\"Cold lathe Head\"\ncn tUok of' Caurrh.\nThose subject to frequent rcoMs la the\"\nb4\" will find that the use of H ALU'S\nywnxuvu aiauiKjina will OUUd up the\n6ytem, cJeanee the Blood and render\nthem lean liable to eolda. Repeated at\ntacks of Acute Catarrh may lead to\nChronlo Catarrh.\nHALL'S CATARRH MEDICINH (a\ngZB&\nreetorlng- normal conditions.\nroaucinK ui innamm&tioit ana\n-urag-gwia. circulars tree.\nF. J. Cheney Co., Toledo, Ohio.\nOne Was Enough.\n\"Could I see Mr. Grumpson?\" askeit\nthe brisk caller.\n\"I suppose so,\" said the clerk, gloom\nily, \"if yoa don't care what happen\nto you. I got one good look at him as\ntie came in this morning and I assure\nyou that will last me all day.\" Bir\nmingham Age-Herald.\nIf the conceit were taken out of\nsome people there would be nothing\nleft to bury.\nHealth fa the fashion. Take Garfield\nTea. the herb laxative which Duritiea the\nblood and brings good health. Adv.\nIn the golden chain of friendshi